WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.760
Give me a hand in welcoming Joshua Cook, who will be talking about Quarto as a multifaceted

00:00:04.760 --> 00:00:12.080
publishing powerhouse.

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:13.320
Thank you so much for having me.

00:00:13.320 --> 00:00:17.480
I look up to a lot of the people in this room, so it's a real honor to present today.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:18.480
My name is Joshua Cook.

00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:20.120
I'm from the University of West Florida.

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:22.080
Here's a little bit about me.

00:00:22.080 --> 00:00:25.799
I recently graduated this past May with my master's in data science.

00:00:25.799 --> 00:00:30.520
Before that, I was in clinical research, and then before that, I was in biomed.

00:00:30.520 --> 00:00:32.680
Right now, I'm an adjunct professor at the university.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:37.000
I teach anatomy and physiology, and I work with a lot of Ph.D. researchers and a lot

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:38.160
of physicians.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:42.080
I was a research quality analyst and a clinical research coordinator for a year before that.

00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:45.360
Actually, for three years before that.

00:00:45.360 --> 00:00:46.360
Medical research.

00:00:46.360 --> 00:00:47.840
I've heard a lot about pharma.

00:00:47.840 --> 00:00:50.799
I want to insert my background a little bit here.

00:00:50.799 --> 00:00:52.200
I have never worked in pharma.

00:00:52.200 --> 00:00:54.959
I've never done clinical trials data.

00:00:55.119 --> 00:00:56.119
I'd like to.

00:00:56.119 --> 00:01:00.439
I'd like to learn it and get into it, but my experience has mostly been with phase one

00:01:00.439 --> 00:01:03.119
clinical trials or benchtop studies.

00:01:03.119 --> 00:01:04.559
That's mostly in academia.

00:01:04.559 --> 00:01:07.239
Sometimes you'll get it done in healthcare and industry.

00:01:07.239 --> 00:01:13.040
When I talk about medical researchers, I'm talking about M.D.'s, D.O.'s, nurse practitioners,

00:01:13.040 --> 00:01:18.279
occasionally Ph.D.'s, or if you're responsible for preparing documents for somebody in this

00:01:18.279 --> 00:01:20.120
category.

00:01:20.120 --> 00:01:21.559
The general process.

00:01:21.559 --> 00:01:23.080
You start with study planning.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.720
You initiate your study.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:27.959
There's some data collection, data analysis, and then dissemination.

00:01:27.959 --> 00:01:32.480
Pretty similar to clinical research, except that we don't have as strict guidelines in

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:37.559
terms of our data structure, and then these are usually, like I said, in academia and

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:39.000
stuff like that.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:40.919
The publication needs are a little bit different.

00:01:40.919 --> 00:01:43.239
Our main goal is not a regulatory submission.

00:01:43.239 --> 00:01:46.760
I've only ever worked on one or two of those briefly before.

00:01:46.760 --> 00:01:52.360
My main goal in my roles has been statistical reports, and sometimes there'll be a simulation

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.760
study before the report.

00:01:54.760 --> 00:01:56.680
Interim reports while a study's going on.

00:01:56.680 --> 00:02:02.480
Interim presentations, if a doctor or a Ph.D. is going to give a presentation at a conference

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:07.120
and the study's still ongoing, and then when it's done, a final report, a final presentation

00:02:07.120 --> 00:02:09.080
for them to go present again.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:11.960
They usually want the manuscript submitted as soon as possible.

00:02:11.960 --> 00:02:13.440
They want a blurb for their website.

00:02:13.440 --> 00:02:19.240
They want it on their blog, and then there's usually this new idea around patient-participant

00:02:19.240 --> 00:02:20.360
material.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:25.000
The patients themselves are starting to ask for their results back, so whenever you have

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.839
people that are taking part in a clinical trial, they've been in it for six months,

00:02:28.839 --> 00:02:30.639
they want to know what their labs have been looking like.

00:02:30.639 --> 00:02:36.839
Well, it's very, very hard to extract that if you're entering data into an EMR or some

00:02:36.839 --> 00:02:41.080
dense medical system, and so being able to very quickly extract that information for

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:45.320
that patient and then allow the doctor to have a presentation on hand to talk with them

00:02:45.320 --> 00:02:47.119
at their next visit's really helpful.

00:02:47.119 --> 00:02:50.320
Finally, sometimes there will be a regulatory submission.

00:02:50.320 --> 00:02:53.639
Just in summary, this is a lot of work to keep up with for medical researchers, people

00:02:53.639 --> 00:02:58.160
who are not used to coding, people who don't do submissions, especially if changes are

00:02:58.160 --> 00:02:59.160
made.

00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:02.800
Many, many times a doctor will look at my statistical report and say, it's great, and

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:06.559
then they're getting ready for their presentation, they're actually out there, they're not at

00:03:06.559 --> 00:03:11.399
the institution anymore, and they're texting me, I need you to update figure one as quickly

00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:12.399
as possible.

00:03:12.399 --> 00:03:15.520
Well, I do that for them, but then every single document that I made before that's out of

00:03:15.520 --> 00:03:16.520
date.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:20.199
So that's really what my presentation is focused on, is how do we use Quarto to make it to

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:25.679
where when I update one document for the physician or the researcher, everything else updates

00:03:25.679 --> 00:03:30.160
with it, we have a change log, we have something to say what it looked like before.

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.199
So here's the traditional method.

00:03:32.199 --> 00:03:37.600
You draft an initial document, everybody approves, all documents are generated, I've got a report,

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.559
a presentation, et cetera.

00:03:39.559 --> 00:03:44.199
Then I get a random edit request, I update the report, and then I frantically copy-paste

00:03:44.199 --> 00:03:47.720
everything that I updated into all the subsequent versions.

00:03:47.720 --> 00:03:51.960
So yes, the doctor wanted figure one to be different, but now I've got to change it everywhere

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:52.960
else.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:58.320
During that time, something gets missed, an error is made, or some more edits have been

00:03:58.320 --> 00:04:00.440
requested since the first request.

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:04.360
Then the author, the medical researcher will go out and present, and they accidentally

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:07.880
present something that's not true, or some outdated piece of information.

00:04:07.880 --> 00:04:11.960
They get frustrated with me, the stakeholders are frustrated, and then we continuously repeat

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:12.960
this process.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:16.980
It looks like some of you have experienced this before, so that's good.

00:04:16.980 --> 00:04:20.459
This is where Korto comes in handy, it's the next generation of R Markdown, I won't go

00:04:20.459 --> 00:04:24.540
too deep into what Korto is, I think everybody is aware at this point.

00:04:24.540 --> 00:04:28.220
But with Korto projects, it allows you to create various project types from a single

00:04:28.220 --> 00:04:29.220
source.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:32.660
And when I talk about project types, I'm talking about an organization of files.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:36.339
So we're familiar with reports, and manuscripts, and presentations.

00:04:36.339 --> 00:04:39.359
This could also be a Korto website, or Korto blog.

00:04:39.359 --> 00:04:43.500
And then when I talk about project formats, I'm talking about how it's going to be output

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:47.660
in the end, an HTML, a PDF, or a .docx.

00:04:47.660 --> 00:04:53.100
So a general setup with Korto, as with any project in RStudio, you need a primary folder.

00:04:53.100 --> 00:04:55.940
I'll go over my folder structure in just a minute.

00:04:55.940 --> 00:04:59.779
These Korto projects are the directories, they're the central location for all of your

00:04:59.779 --> 00:05:04.459
folders, your images, your scripts, and then any output that you're going to generate.

00:05:04.459 --> 00:05:06.899
This is a key concept for this presentation.

00:05:06.899 --> 00:05:10.220
We're going to do three different projects today in this talk.

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:13.660
We're going to generate a report, we're going to generate a manuscript, and we're going

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:18.660
to generate a presentation with templates, all from the same source code.

00:05:18.660 --> 00:05:22.459
So Korto projects, they have this shared YAML for metadata.

00:05:22.459 --> 00:05:25.700
Each of the project types typically have a different setup for their YAML.

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.859
I've got examples in here.

00:05:27.859 --> 00:05:31.179
But when you're in RStudio, all you have to do is click the create project button.

00:05:31.179 --> 00:05:35.140
It gives you an option to include a directory name and change where your working directory

00:05:35.140 --> 00:05:36.220
is going to be at.

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:38.779
And then finally, in project type, you can start setting these things up.

00:05:38.779 --> 00:05:41.940
So Korto website, blog, book, manuscript, they're all listed there.

00:05:41.940 --> 00:05:42.940
It's very easy to click them.

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.260
There's also terminal commands to set these up.

00:05:45.260 --> 00:05:46.700
It's pretty straightforward.

00:05:46.700 --> 00:05:50.420
Whenever you start a new Korto document, it's going to give you a template file,

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.940
usually index.qmd.

00:05:52.940 --> 00:05:56.019
It comes with some markdown code, and there's an example below.

00:05:56.019 --> 00:05:58.459
It also includes a very basic YAML header.

00:05:58.459 --> 00:06:03.059
The title is the only thing in this one, and then an example R code chunk.

00:06:03.059 --> 00:06:04.899
You can change the language if you want to.

00:06:04.899 --> 00:06:07.540
If you don't want to use R and you want to use Python, that's supported.

00:06:07.540 --> 00:06:09.859
So is Julia and a couple other languages.

00:06:09.859 --> 00:06:14.980
Toolbar gives you very easy access to editing tools without knowing markdown

00:06:14.980 --> 00:06:16.059
syntax.

00:06:16.059 --> 00:06:17.339
And this is just the basic layout.

00:06:17.339 --> 00:06:21.299
So you can continue to add chunks and markdown content as you need.

00:06:21.299 --> 00:06:23.500
The YAML header is very, very important.

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:28.179
This is a versatile human-readable data serialization language.

00:06:28.179 --> 00:06:32.100
This is where you configure how your document is going to populate.

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:34.820
So you'll see throughout my examples today, a lot of front matter.

00:06:34.820 --> 00:06:37.980
The title, the subtitle, date, author, et cetera.

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:41.940
The important sections are format, which designates the output format.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:44.380
This is also where I designate all of my templates.

00:06:44.380 --> 00:06:48.500
So if you're interested in, oh, my author usually generates manuscripts

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:50.140
for a very specific journal.

00:06:50.140 --> 00:06:52.899
I use the Public Library of Science in my example.

00:06:52.899 --> 00:06:56.059
You can download that template, and then it will automatically output to that

00:06:56.059 --> 00:06:58.299
when you render the PDF.

00:06:58.299 --> 00:06:59.700
There's a bunch of YAML options.

00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:02.779
I included a link to go explore more.

00:07:02.779 --> 00:07:06.579
But here's my case example for medical researchers.

00:07:06.579 --> 00:07:08.260
So this is the file structure.

00:07:08.260 --> 00:07:10.500
My working directory is called PositConf.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:14.260
And within PositConf, I have these folders, data, analysis, images,

00:07:14.260 --> 00:07:15.940
manuscript, presentation.

00:07:15.940 --> 00:07:18.779
And then within the working directory itself, I have my report,

00:07:18.779 --> 00:07:22.420
our project, my index.qmd, and my report to YAML.

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:26.100
So the report itself is going to be in the working directory.

00:07:26.100 --> 00:07:31.940
Everything that you're about to see is within this index.qmd down at the bottom.

00:07:31.940 --> 00:07:34.859
All right, so in my report, it's very, very simple.

00:07:34.859 --> 00:07:38.299
I have this front matter where I'm supplying a title, a logo,

00:07:38.299 --> 00:07:40.739
the author names, and the date.

00:07:40.739 --> 00:07:43.220
This section is what you probably want to pay attention to.

00:07:43.220 --> 00:07:46.619
This is telling it that it should be output as an HTML document,

00:07:46.619 --> 00:07:49.380
don't mess with my tables, and embed all the resources so it doesn't have

00:07:49.380 --> 00:07:51.179
any dependencies.

00:07:51.179 --> 00:07:53.739
And then you can hit Render, and it will populate with all the front

00:07:53.739 --> 00:07:55.579
matter that I specified.

00:07:55.579 --> 00:07:59.019
I also added in a code chunk that is not being executed,

00:07:59.019 --> 00:08:03.140
but my lead statistician may want to review, so I included my code.

00:08:03.140 --> 00:08:04.420
And then I included this figure.

00:08:04.420 --> 00:08:08.299
This figure is an analysis of all the missing data in our dataset.

00:08:08.299 --> 00:08:12.420
Now, importantly, neither of these things are coded directly

00:08:12.420 --> 00:08:14.940
within my report.

00:08:14.940 --> 00:08:17.619
You'll see that I use what's called shortcodes.

00:08:17.619 --> 00:08:21.420
So in a nutshell, the goal of this is to maintain quality and consistency

00:08:21.420 --> 00:08:22.859
through modularity.

00:08:22.859 --> 00:08:26.260
Quarto shortcodes are special markdown directives that generate our content

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:27.540
from another file.

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:32.659
So if you look back at my file directory, all of my actual QMD files are

00:08:32.659 --> 00:08:34.260
in this analysis folder.

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:36.500
I'm not doing anything within the Quarto markdown.

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:38.020
It's not hosted locally.

00:08:38.020 --> 00:08:40.739
It's just pulling from this QMD.

00:08:40.739 --> 00:08:43.059
All the data is in one separate file.

00:08:43.059 --> 00:08:49.299
It's not being generated and brought into R each time I want to do a report.

00:08:49.299 --> 00:08:52.419
And then down here, you can see there's two types of shortcodes I use.

00:08:52.419 --> 00:08:55.859
The first one is embed, which directly embeds that Quarto markdown file

00:08:55.859 --> 00:08:59.979
or Jupyter Notebook into my report, my presentation, my manuscript.

00:08:59.979 --> 00:09:02.299
It's just going to run the code that's there.

00:09:02.299 --> 00:09:05.900
And if you're not careful, it will copy in everything that's in that QMD.

00:09:05.900 --> 00:09:09.059
So everything that's generated will be put into your document.

00:09:09.059 --> 00:09:12.380
You can specify what you want, though, using hashtags.

00:09:12.380 --> 00:09:15.099
And then include is a direct copy-paste.

00:09:15.099 --> 00:09:17.820
So it's not embedding the QMD.

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:21.820
It is just grabbing the code and then running it in your main file.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:26.460
The example of the include shortcode is on line one.

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:29.619
I didn't specify any particular figure, so it's going to throw everything that's

00:09:29.619 --> 00:09:34.780
in my data processing QMD, everything that's being output into my documents.

00:09:34.780 --> 00:09:36.940
The second one is an example of embed.

00:09:36.940 --> 00:09:39.020
And you'll see that there's a hashtag.

00:09:39.020 --> 00:09:41.940
That's where I specified, I only want figure one.

00:09:41.940 --> 00:09:44.780
There's a bunch of other figures in there that I was doing as part of EDA,

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:49.940
but this saves time and processing and makes sure you only grab what you want.

00:09:49.940 --> 00:09:53.340
So here's the YAML for my manuscript that's in the manuscript folder.

00:09:53.340 --> 00:09:56.500
It's a little bit different, pretty much the same front matter

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.500
that I copy-pasted.

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:00.099
But this time, it is a PDF.

00:10:00.099 --> 00:10:02.179
Most manuscripts want a PDF.

00:10:02.179 --> 00:10:03.580
And then I specified a template.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:08.940
So please use the Public Library of Science, specifically for Global Public

00:10:08.940 --> 00:10:09.219
Health.

00:10:09.219 --> 00:10:10.859
This was a public health study.

00:10:10.859 --> 00:10:14.020
That way, any specific formatting that needs to be done is automatically going

00:10:14.020 --> 00:10:15.580
to be applied.

00:10:15.580 --> 00:10:17.859
Here's the manuscript, again, with all the front matter.

00:10:17.859 --> 00:10:20.219
And importantly, it's that same exact figure.

00:10:20.219 --> 00:10:24.580
Figure's not being generated within the manuscript QMD itself.

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:26.299
I'm doing it using shortcodes.

00:10:26.299 --> 00:10:32.140
So I just want to keep using that idea of never include all of your code in one

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:35.099
cortomarkdown because every time you render, it's got a process.

00:10:35.099 --> 00:10:39.739
And then if you change one thing there, since it's not being shortcoded in,

00:10:39.739 --> 00:10:43.859
you have to go change it everywhere else you mention that figure.

00:10:43.859 --> 00:10:47.940
And then finally, for the presentation, same thing, same front matter,

00:10:47.940 --> 00:10:49.979
little bit more complicated YAML header.

00:10:49.979 --> 00:10:55.059
I had to specify not only a template, which in this case is a Reveal JavaScript

00:10:55.059 --> 00:10:58.299
template called Clean, but also self-contained preview links.

00:10:58.299 --> 00:11:01.099
There's a couple different features you can add in that are really similar

00:11:01.099 --> 00:11:02.260
to PowerPoint.

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:05.739
So if your medical researcher is used to PowerPoint or to Keynote,

00:11:05.739 --> 00:11:07.859
they may want those things in there.

00:11:07.859 --> 00:11:11.380
And then everything else is front matter.

00:11:11.380 --> 00:11:12.260
So here's the presentation.

00:11:12.260 --> 00:11:15.099
It's the same exact template that I used for this talk.

00:11:15.099 --> 00:11:19.140
It's the title, all of the front matter that I mentioned before, the logo,

00:11:19.140 --> 00:11:24.419
same exact figure being shortcoded in one line of code from my analysis script.

00:11:24.419 --> 00:11:28.940
Now, importantly, when that medical researcher comes back to me as they're

00:11:28.940 --> 00:11:31.380
about to present this in five minutes and they say,

00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:34.460
figure one is wrong, I want you to update the caption.

00:11:34.460 --> 00:11:40.179
As long as I go do it in my data processing QMD, whenever I go to re-render

00:11:40.179 --> 00:11:43.500
these documents, that change will be applied everywhere because I

00:11:43.500 --> 00:11:46.460
used shortcodes.

00:11:46.460 --> 00:11:51.219
I've been in the mix where things kind of get messed up, where they have a certain

00:11:51.219 --> 00:11:54.700
copy that I generated last week, and then I generated this new copy,

00:11:54.700 --> 00:11:56.780
and everything's just a mess.

00:11:56.780 --> 00:11:59.299
This saves that, especially if you're using GitHub, because then you can track

00:11:59.299 --> 00:12:03.099
your changes as everything is taking place.

00:12:03.099 --> 00:12:06.460
And then furthermore, researchers don't know how to use Reveal

00:12:06.460 --> 00:12:07.500
JavaScript sometimes.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.859
They prefer PowerPoint, Keynote, that's fine.

00:12:09.859 --> 00:12:14.219
You can just change the format to PPTX, and then it will output those figures,

00:12:14.219 --> 00:12:19.099
those tables, the inline code that you referenced into a PowerPoint format.

00:12:19.099 --> 00:12:23.059
That way, the only thing they really have to do is copy that slide from your new

00:12:23.059 --> 00:12:25.580
output into their existing presentation.

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:26.900
That makes it very quick and easy.

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:28.780
They don't have to worry about resizing.

00:12:28.780 --> 00:12:31.140
There's no messy screenshotting of reports.

00:12:31.140 --> 00:12:33.539
It's what physicians have done with me in the past.

00:12:33.539 --> 00:12:36.099
It's also in the updated report, they just take a screenshot of what I

00:12:36.099 --> 00:12:38.179
generated and the whole thing's messed up.

00:12:38.179 --> 00:12:42.179
But yeah, everything will update for their new presentation.

00:12:42.179 --> 00:12:44.739
So in this case example, this is really important because all

00:12:44.739 --> 00:12:47.419
of these documents are frequently used by medical researchers.

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:52.140
And you could expand it further to Quarto websites, blogs, or other types of projects

00:12:52.140 --> 00:12:55.859
where maybe they have a website, where they have a research portfolio,

00:12:55.859 --> 00:12:57.659
maybe they're applying for grants.

00:12:57.659 --> 00:12:59.460
I've heard all of those things.

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:01.219
You could add that in there as well.

00:13:01.219 --> 00:13:05.580
As you're updating your one QMD file, every subsequent Quarto output is

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:06.900
going to update.

00:13:06.900 --> 00:13:10.580
If an error is identified or something else, simply altering those files will

00:13:10.580 --> 00:13:12.619
queue them to refresh.

00:13:12.619 --> 00:13:16.979
And I'll show you a setting in a second that you have to put into the Quarto YAML

00:13:16.979 --> 00:13:19.340
to kind of freeze at that time point.

00:13:19.340 --> 00:13:24.419
And then anytime there is a change detected, it will re-render that document.

00:13:24.419 --> 00:13:27.820
If another template is needed, we've all been rejected from journals before.

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:31.299
This is probably one of the biggest time-saving tasks that I've had is we'll

00:13:31.299 --> 00:13:33.659
submit to the Public Library of Science, and they'll reject us.

00:13:33.659 --> 00:13:36.020
And then we'll say, okay, submit to Nature.

00:13:36.020 --> 00:13:39.780
Well, then you have to go reformat the references, the figures,

00:13:39.780 --> 00:13:42.299
the file structure, everything needs to be changed.

00:13:42.299 --> 00:13:46.619
Instead, why not just enter in one line of code to change the template

00:13:46.619 --> 00:13:49.780
over to Nature, and then specify that in your YAML header?

00:13:49.780 --> 00:13:52.179
Everything else will be automatically rearranged.

00:13:52.179 --> 00:13:56.219
The only catch is some journals require you to submit figures and tables

00:13:56.219 --> 00:13:57.219
separately.

00:13:57.219 --> 00:14:01.179
In that case, you will want to disable the generation and then just save them

00:14:01.179 --> 00:14:03.299
natively to a file.

00:14:03.299 --> 00:14:06.739
So even if the researcher prefers traditional PowerPoint or Word,

00:14:06.739 --> 00:14:08.020
you can still output to those.

00:14:08.020 --> 00:14:10.419
It just gets a little bit tricky with tracking.

00:14:10.419 --> 00:14:13.059
Still recommend to protect against redundancy when updating your

00:14:13.059 --> 00:14:14.700
analysis code though.

00:14:14.700 --> 00:14:17.539
And then, in other words, we are effectively moving beyond

00:14:17.539 --> 00:14:18.140
copy-paste.

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:22.059
We're making it to where they no longer have to take the report and screenshot

00:14:22.059 --> 00:14:23.260
whatever change I made.

00:14:23.260 --> 00:14:25.179
It's automatically in all their documents.

00:14:25.179 --> 00:14:28.739
If they have access to the directory that I'm outputting these documents to,

00:14:28.739 --> 00:14:31.700
maybe if it's on a shared drive or something like that, I can just say,

00:14:31.700 --> 00:14:34.820
hey, every document that you need is now in the updated drive.

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:39.979
Saves me a ton of work and it's really efficient for submissions.

00:14:39.979 --> 00:14:44.739
So to wrap up, there's a bunch of advanced features that I didn't want to spend time

00:14:44.739 --> 00:14:47.700
going into because I could spend a whole lecture on them.

00:14:47.700 --> 00:14:49.500
But the first one is inline programming.

00:14:49.500 --> 00:14:54.179
So again, instead of copy-pasting values from tables or from figures,

00:14:54.179 --> 00:14:57.539
which can change, you know, I go back and update the analysis code,

00:14:57.539 --> 00:15:00.700
suddenly the mean has changed by two units.

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:01.820
Just use inline programming.

00:15:01.820 --> 00:15:04.820
So that can make sure that no matter what format you're outputting to,

00:15:04.820 --> 00:15:07.179
that value is being pulled from my actual analysis.

00:15:07.179 --> 00:15:10.059
It's not being copy-pasted from somebody else.

00:15:10.059 --> 00:15:14.179
Second one is everything's dynamically updating based on the quarto.yaml file.

00:15:14.179 --> 00:15:18.700
So under execute, there is a freeze function and typically it's set to true.

00:15:18.700 --> 00:15:23.659
If you set it to auto, it will automatically re-render files

00:15:23.659 --> 00:15:25.419
if changes are detected.

00:15:25.419 --> 00:15:31.299
So let's say you want to render a report and everything's fine.

00:15:31.299 --> 00:15:34.580
You don't want to keep re-rendering that processing file because it takes time

00:15:34.580 --> 00:15:37.380
and computational power, especially if nothing's changing.

00:15:37.380 --> 00:15:41.020
Only change if somebody has gone in there and edited something.

00:15:41.020 --> 00:15:41.979
Number three is templates.

00:15:41.979 --> 00:15:45.419
I used a template today for the manuscript and for the presentation.

00:15:45.419 --> 00:15:47.380
There's plenty of open-source templates online.

00:15:47.380 --> 00:15:51.099
So if you have a specific use case or a specific journal that you're always

00:15:51.099 --> 00:15:53.179
submitting to, I highly recommend using them.

00:15:53.179 --> 00:15:57.299
I will never personally format by hand for specific journals anymore

00:15:57.299 --> 00:15:58.979
after figuring this out.

00:15:58.979 --> 00:16:00.820
Number four is collaboration tools.

00:16:00.820 --> 00:16:03.419
With a little bit of setup, you can set up a hypothesis which allows

00:16:03.419 --> 00:16:06.619
for commenting notes and highlights, which is what medical researchers are used

00:16:06.619 --> 00:16:09.460
to with track changes and Word documents.

00:16:09.460 --> 00:16:12.619
This works with Zotero libraries for reference tracking, which is great.

00:16:12.619 --> 00:16:13.739
Zotero is free.

00:16:13.739 --> 00:16:17.219
It can import references from PubMed and other sources and then input them

00:16:17.219 --> 00:16:19.580
into your references within Quartet Markdown.

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:23.140
There's also some compatibility with EndNote, but you have to do some trickery

00:16:23.140 --> 00:16:25.659
because it is proprietary software.

00:16:25.659 --> 00:16:28.900
Number six, hopefully, this will enhance patient communication.

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:31.020
Very quick release of their documents when they're wondering where they're

00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:31.700
at in a study.

00:16:31.700 --> 00:16:32.500
It's their data.

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:35.500
They have a right to see it, especially if there's nothing stopping them

00:16:35.500 --> 00:16:38.260
from unblinding or any other concerns in the protocol.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.780
And then number seven, hopefully, this will speed up the delivery

00:16:40.780 --> 00:16:44.020
of treatments because physicians and other medical researchers no longer have

00:16:44.020 --> 00:16:47.739
to spend time converting my statistical report into their manuscript,

00:16:47.739 --> 00:16:50.580
into their presentation, into their website.

00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:54.219
So, in conclusion, Quarto is a multifaceted publishing powerhouse

00:16:54.219 --> 00:16:57.820
for medical researchers that allows us to efficiently create these polished formats

00:16:57.820 --> 00:16:59.460
from a single-source document.

00:16:59.460 --> 00:17:02.979
There's templates available to support a wide array of submission requirements.

00:17:02.979 --> 00:17:04.819
There's tools for collaboration.

00:17:04.819 --> 00:17:08.500
And this will hopefully enhance participant communication and the speed

00:17:08.500 --> 00:17:11.380
of delivery to patients.

00:17:11.380 --> 00:17:15.099
Limitations, the setup and organisation may not be appropriate if your project

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:15.699
is small.

00:17:15.699 --> 00:17:18.660
This is a little bit of heavy lifting at the front end.

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:21.859
Tables seem to have a problem with the embed shortcode.

00:17:21.859 --> 00:17:22.900
Not sure on a fix yet.

00:17:22.900 --> 00:17:26.420
I just, you know, coded directly into the Quarto markdown.

00:17:26.420 --> 00:17:29.380
And then I really want to think about ways to reuse the markdown text

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:33.260
because we found a way to reuse our code, inserting the same exact figure

00:17:33.260 --> 00:17:34.140
into multiple outputs.

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:37.739
What about all of the context that you're adding in markdown?

00:17:37.739 --> 00:17:40.260
How do we take that, maybe with a large language model,

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:43.339
and repurpose it for other formats?

00:17:43.339 --> 00:17:44.859
And that's it.

00:17:44.859 --> 00:17:48.219
I want to thank my partner, Nathaniel Nicholas, and my mentors over the years,

00:17:48.219 --> 00:17:50.540
and Mine, who gave a great talk.

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:51.219
I linked it here.

00:17:51.219 --> 00:17:53.859
She did a very similar presentation on Quarto.

00:17:53.859 --> 00:17:56.459
My QR code is here if you guys have any questions.

00:17:56.459 --> 00:17:59.900
And I am actively seeking a full-time position if there's any people

00:17:59.900 --> 00:18:00.420
in the audience.

00:18:00.420 --> 00:18:01.420
Thank you so much.

00:18:01.420 --> 00:18:10.420
Thank you.

00:18:10.420 --> 00:18:13.300
Thank you.

00:18:13.300 --> 00:18:13.900
Get the mic.

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:14.579
Yep, there we go.

00:18:14.579 --> 00:18:15.140
Thank you, Joshua.

00:18:15.140 --> 00:18:16.619
That was a great talk.

00:18:16.619 --> 00:18:17.579
Quick question here.

00:18:17.579 --> 00:18:21.939
Have you ever experienced any resistance to using Quarto for slides instead

00:18:21.939 --> 00:18:24.739
of PowerPoint that the presenter can edit last minute?

00:18:24.739 --> 00:18:28.099
And I guess my follow-up on top of that is it seems like a PowerPoint is

00:18:28.099 --> 00:18:29.300
an output option.

00:18:29.300 --> 00:18:32.180
So how do you know that they're not editing it last minute?

00:18:32.180 --> 00:18:35.380
So typically, they can't edit my figures because the figures are being

00:18:35.380 --> 00:18:36.300
outputted as an image.

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:40.900
And so they'll email me or text me, hey, I need you to update figure two.

00:18:40.900 --> 00:18:44.699
In that case, I know they need me, and I will just re-output the PowerPoint.

00:18:44.699 --> 00:18:48.540
And then they can copy that whole slide from my output of PowerPoint into their

00:18:48.540 --> 00:18:49.699
final PowerPoint.

00:18:49.699 --> 00:18:50.859
That makes it very quick and easy.

00:18:50.859 --> 00:18:53.380
If they're editing content, that's their own thing.

00:18:53.380 --> 00:18:55.260
I don't add content to the slides.

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:58.619
Typically, I don't have the background to do that, and many of us don't.

00:18:58.619 --> 00:19:01.500
If we want to talk about, you know, latest developments in cancer research,

00:19:01.500 --> 00:19:04.500
that's all on the physician or medical researcher.

00:19:04.500 --> 00:19:05.060
Great.

00:19:05.060 --> 00:19:05.900
Thank you so much.

00:19:05.900 --> 00:19:06.900
Thank you.

